&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Decibels&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Decibels (dB)&lt;/strong&gt; are the preferred unit for expressing the &lt;strong&gt;ratio between two sound intensities&lt;/strong&gt;. It is widely used in scientific literature, acoustics, and engineering fields.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The decibel scale is &lt;strong&gt;logarithmic&lt;/strong&gt;, meaning a small change in decibels represents a significant change in sound intensity. It helps in expressing very large or very small ratios conveniently.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Decibels are calculated using the formula: &lt;strong&gt;10 &amp;times; log10(P2/P1)&lt;/strong&gt;, where P2 and P1 represent two sound intensities or powers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This unit is commonly used for measuring &lt;strong&gt;sound levels, electrical power, and signal strength&lt;/strong&gt;, making it versatile across multiple scientific domains.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Decibels simplify the representation of sound levels, where 0 dB is the threshold of hearing, and values like 120 dB represent sounds at the threshold of pain.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Phon:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Phon&lt;/strong&gt; is a unit used to measure the &lt;strong&gt;perceived loudness&lt;/strong&gt; of sound by humans. It accounts for the sensitivity of the human ear to different frequencies but is not typically used in calculating sound intensity ratios.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The phon scale is based on comparisons to a reference tone of 1 kHz.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Pascal:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Pascal (Pa)&lt;/strong&gt; is the SI unit of pressure. It is used to measure the &lt;strong&gt;pressure exerted by sound waves&lt;/strong&gt;, not the ratio between two sound intensities.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For sound, pressure levels are expressed in micropascals (&amp;mu;Pa), but this is more relevant to physical pressure than intensity ratios.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hertz:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hertz (Hz)&lt;/strong&gt; is the SI unit for frequency, representing the number of cycles of a sound wave per second. It is used to describe the pitch of a sound, not the intensity.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Frequency ranges like 20 Hz to 20 kHz are considered the audible range for humans.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications of Decibels:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Decibels are widely used in acoustics to measure &lt;strong&gt;sound pressure levels&lt;/strong&gt; and noise pollution.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They are also employed in electronics to express &lt;strong&gt;signal-to-noise ratios&lt;/strong&gt;, amplifier gains, and attenuation.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In telecommunications, decibels are used to quantify &lt;strong&gt;signal power&lt;/strong&gt; and transmission loss.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logarithmic Nature:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The logarithmic nature of decibels enables efficient representation of very large or small sound intensity ratios.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It also reflects human perception of sound, where doubling the sound intensity does not equate to doubling the perceived loudness.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Thresholds:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The threshold of hearing is approximately &lt;strong&gt;0 dB&lt;/strong&gt;, while the threshold of pain is around &lt;strong&gt;120 dB&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Common sound levels include &lt;strong&gt;60 dB&lt;/strong&gt; for normal conversation and &lt;strong&gt;90 dB&lt;/strong&gt; for heavy traffic noise.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Decibels in Other Fields:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In electrical engineering, decibels express the &lt;strong&gt;power gain&lt;/strong&gt; of amplifiers or attenuation of filters.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In telecommunications, they measure &lt;strong&gt;signal loss or gain&lt;/strong&gt; during transmission.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p data-end=&quot;57&quot; data-start=&quot;0&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Vitamins&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p data-end=&quot;57&quot; data-start=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;284&quot; data-start=&quot;78&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Micronutrients&lt;/strong&gt; are essential nutrients required by the body in small amounts for proper physiological functioning. These include &lt;strong&gt;vitamins&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;minerals&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;605&quot; data-start=&quot;482&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Vitamins&lt;/strong&gt; are classified as micronutrients because they are required in minute quantities and play a vital role in various biochemical processes. For example, Vitamin A is crucial for vision, while Vitamin C supports immune functions. &lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Hence, option 2 is correct.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;692&quot; data-start=&quot;610&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Proteins&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;fats&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;carbohydrates&lt;/strong&gt; are macronutrients, not micronutrients. They are required in larger quantities to provide energy, build and repair tissues, and support overall body functions. &lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Hence, options 1, 3, and 4 are incorrect.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;1041&quot; data-start=&quot;850&quot;&gt;Micronutrients, such as &lt;strong&gt;vitamins&lt;/strong&gt;, are vital for regulating metabolism, maintaining cellular functions, and preventing diseases. Deficiency in micronutrients can lead to health issues like scurvy (Vitamin C deficiency) or rickets (Vitamin D deficiency).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;1162&quot; data-start=&quot;1046&quot;&gt;Unlike macronutrients, micronutrients do not provide energy but are indispensable for maintaining optimal health and biochemical activities.&amp;nbsp;&lt;em style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Hence, the correct answer is Vitamins.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Characteristics of Micronutrients:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2410&quot; data-start=&quot;2195&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Micronutrients&lt;/strong&gt; include &lt;strong&gt;vitamins&lt;/strong&gt; (e.g., Vitamin A, B-complex, Vitamin C, Vitamin D, Vitamin E, Vitamin K) and &lt;strong&gt;minerals&lt;/strong&gt; (e.g., iron, zinc, magnesium, calcium).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2684&quot; data-start=&quot;2415&quot;&gt;They are required in very small amounts, usually measured in milligrams or micrograms, but their impact on health is significant.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2860&quot; data-start=&quot;2735&quot;&gt;Micronutrients are obtained primarily from a balanced diet, including fruits, vegetables, grains, and animal products.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Functions of Vitamins:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3250&quot; data-start=&quot;3076&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Vitamin A:&lt;/strong&gt; Supports vision, immune health, and skin integrity.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3402&quot; data-start=&quot;3301&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Vitamin B-complex:&lt;/strong&gt; Helps in energy metabolism and supports nervous system functions.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3580&quot; data-start=&quot;3407&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Vitamin C:&lt;/strong&gt; Boosts immunity and aids in collagen synthesis.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3729&quot; data-start=&quot;3585&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Vitamin D:&lt;/strong&gt; Regulates calcium absorption and bone health.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3860&quot; data-start=&quot;3730&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Vitamin K:&lt;/strong&gt; Essential for blood clotting and bone health.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sources of Micronutrients:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;4040&quot; data-start=&quot;3900&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Vitamins:&lt;/strong&gt; Found in fruits, vegetables, dairy products, meat, and fortified foods.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;4210&quot; data-start=&quot;4050&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Minerals:&lt;/strong&gt; Found in leafy vegetables, nuts, seeds, meat, and seafood.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;4360&quot; data-start=&quot;4220&quot;&gt;A balanced diet is essential for meeting micronutrient requirements and preventing deficiencies.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Differences Between Micronutrients and Macronutrients:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;4636&quot; data-start=&quot;4411&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Micronutrients:&lt;/strong&gt; Required in small quantities; include vitamins and minerals.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;4761&quot; data-start=&quot;4641&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Macronutrients:&lt;/strong&gt; Required in larger quantities; include proteins, fats, and carbohydrates.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;4890&quot; data-start=&quot;4770&quot;&gt;Micronutrients do not provide energy but are crucial for biochemical functions, whereas macronutrients serve as energy sources.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Health Implications:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;5043&quot; data-start=&quot;4817&quot;&gt;Deficiency in micronutrients can lead to conditions such as anemia (iron deficiency), scurvy (Vitamin C deficiency), or osteoporosis (calcium and Vitamin D deficiency).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;5259&quot; data-start=&quot;5048&quot;&gt;Excessive intake of certain micronutrients can also result in toxicity. For example, excessive Vitamin A can lead to hypervitaminosis A.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;RuBisCO&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;RuBisCO (Ribulose-1,5-bisphosphate carboxylase/oxygenase)&lt;/strong&gt; is widely regarded as the most abundant protein in the biosphere. It plays a critical role in the process of &lt;strong&gt;photosynthesis&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This enzyme is responsible for fixing atmospheric &lt;strong&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/strong&gt; into organic molecules during the Calvin cycle in plants, algae, and cyanobacteria.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;RuBisCO is found in the chloroplasts of plants and other photosynthetic organisms. Its abundance is due to its essential role in photosynthesis and the massive biomass of photosynthetic organisms on Earth.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Given its global presence and significance in the carbon cycle, RuBisCO is integral to sustaining life on Earth by contributing to the production of oxygen and organic material.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;While proteins like collagen, myosin, and GLUT-4 are important in animal systems, they do not come close to RuBisCO in terms of abundance globally.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Collagen:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Collagen is a structural protein found predominantly in &lt;strong&gt;animals&lt;/strong&gt;. It is the main component of connective tissues like tendons, cartilage, and skin.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It provides strength and elasticity to tissues and is the most abundant protein in the human body, but not in the biosphere.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Collagen is widely used in medical treatments, cosmetic products, and supplements.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;GLUT-4:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;GLUT-4 is a glucose transporter protein primarily found in &lt;strong&gt;muscle and fat tissues&lt;/strong&gt; of animals.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It plays a critical role in glucose uptake in response to &lt;strong&gt;insulin stimulation&lt;/strong&gt;, thereby contributing to glucose metabolism.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;While important for regulating blood sugar levels, its abundance is limited to specific tissues in animals.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Myosin:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Myosin is a motor protein found in animal cells and is essential for &lt;strong&gt;muscle contraction&lt;/strong&gt; and movement.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It interacts with actin filaments to facilitate cellular motion and is abundant in muscles.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Its abundance is restricted to the animal kingdom and does not match the global prevalence of RuBisCO.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;RuBisCO in detail:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;RuBisCO is a highly inefficient enzyme, making it necessary for plants to produce it in large quantities to sustain the rate of photosynthesis.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is estimated that RuBisCO constitutes up to &lt;strong&gt;50% of the soluble protein&lt;/strong&gt; in plant leaves.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;RuBisCO&amp;#39;s dual functionality allows it to catalyze both carboxylation and oxygenation reactions, although the oxygenation reaction can lead to photorespiration, which is less efficient.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Efforts are underway in scientific research to engineer RuBisCO for improved efficiency to enhance crop yields and carbon fixation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Global significance:&lt;/strong&gt; RuBisCO is critical for maintaining the Earth&amp;#39;s carbon cycle by converting atmospheric &lt;strong&gt;CO&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; into organic material.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Biological diversity:&lt;/strong&gt; RuBisCO is present across various organisms, including &lt;strong&gt;plants, algae, and cyanobacteria&lt;/strong&gt;, making it universally significant.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Research focus:&lt;/strong&gt; Scientists are exploring genetic modifications to increase RuBisCO&amp;#39;s efficiency, aiming to improve agricultural productivity and address climate change challenges.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Environmental impact:&lt;/strong&gt; RuBisCO indirectly contributes to &lt;strong&gt;oxygen production&lt;/strong&gt; and serves as a cornerstone for ecosystems globally.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;RNA has multiple roles including catalytic functions&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;color: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;RNA&lt;/strong&gt; is a versatile molecule that performs various functions essential for life.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In addition to being a genetic material in certain organisms (like viruses), RNA also plays a major role in protein synthesis as &lt;strong&gt;messenger RNA (mRNA), transfer RNA (tRNA), and ribosomal RNA (rRNA).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Certain types of RNA, such as &lt;strong&gt;ribozymes&lt;/strong&gt;, exhibit &lt;strong&gt;catalytic functions&lt;/strong&gt;. Ribozymes catalyze biochemical reactions, such as cleaving RNA molecules or forming peptide bonds during protein synthesis.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The discovery of catalytic RNA challenged the traditional belief that only &lt;strong&gt;proteins&lt;/strong&gt; could act as enzymes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;RNA is involved in processes such as &lt;strong&gt;gene regulation, splicing, and editing&lt;/strong&gt;, highlighting its multifunctional nature.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The ability of RNA to fold into complex three-dimensional structures is crucial for its catalytic and regulatory roles.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Examples of RNA molecules with catalytic functions include &lt;strong&gt;self-splicing introns&lt;/strong&gt; and the &lt;strong&gt;ribosome&lt;/strong&gt;, where rRNA catalyzes peptide bond formation.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;DNA is not present in viruses&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Some viruses, such as &lt;strong&gt;retroviruses&lt;/strong&gt; (e.g., HIV), use RNA as their genetic material instead of DNA.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;However, many viruses, including &lt;strong&gt;adenoviruses and herpesviruses&lt;/strong&gt;, contain DNA as their genetic material. Hence, the statement is incorrect.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;DNA acts only as a messenger molecule&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;DNA is primarily the &lt;strong&gt;repository of genetic information&lt;/strong&gt; in most organisms. It does not function as a messenger molecule; this role is performed by &lt;strong&gt;RNA (mRNA).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;RNA acts solely as genetic material in all living organisms&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In most living organisms, &lt;strong&gt;DNA&lt;/strong&gt; serves as the primary genetic material, while RNA plays supporting roles. Only certain viruses use RNA as their genetic material.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p data-end=&quot;57&quot; data-start=&quot;0&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;NaCl&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p data-end=&quot;57&quot; data-start=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;284&quot; data-start=&quot;78&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ionic Bonding:&lt;/strong&gt; Ionic bonding occurs when atoms transfer electrons to achieve stability. In this type of bond, one atom donates electrons, becoming a positively charged &lt;strong&gt;cation&lt;/strong&gt;, while the other atom accepts electrons, becoming a negatively charged &lt;strong&gt;anion&lt;/strong&gt;. The electrostatic attraction between these oppositely charged ions forms the bond.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;605&quot; data-start=&quot;482&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;NaCl (Sodium Chloride):&lt;/strong&gt; Sodium chloride is a classic example of a compound formed by ionic bonding. In NaCl, &lt;strong&gt;sodium (Na)&lt;/strong&gt; donates one electron to achieve a stable electronic configuration, forming a positive ion (Na⁺). Meanwhile, &lt;strong&gt;chlorine (Cl)&lt;/strong&gt; accepts the electron to complete its octet, forming a negative ion (Cl⁻). The electrostatic attraction between Na⁺ and Cl⁻ ions results in the ionic bond.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;692&quot; data-start=&quot;610&quot;&gt;Compounds like &lt;strong&gt;NaCl&lt;/strong&gt; typically have a crystalline structure due to the arrangement of ions in a lattice format. These compounds exhibit high melting and boiling points and conduct electricity in molten or aqueous states.&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Hence, NaCl is correct.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;1041&quot; data-start=&quot;850&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Other Options:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;1162&quot; data-start=&quot;1046&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;H₂O:&lt;/strong&gt; Water is a covalent compound, not ionic. It forms through sharing of electrons between hydrogen and oxygen atoms.&amp;nbsp;&lt;em style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Hence, incorrect.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;1560&quot; data-start=&quot;1323&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;CO₂:&lt;/strong&gt; Carbon dioxide is also a covalent compound formed by sharing electrons between carbon and oxygen atoms.&amp;nbsp;&lt;em style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Hence, incorrect.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;1654&quot; data-start=&quot;1565&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;NH₃:&lt;/strong&gt; Ammonia is another example of a covalent compound formed by sharing electrons between nitrogen and hydrogen atoms.&amp;nbsp;&lt;em style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Hence, incorrect.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;2112&quot; data-start=&quot;2076&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, the correct answer is &lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;NaCl.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Characteristics of Ionic Compounds:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2410&quot; data-start=&quot;2195&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;High melting and boiling points:&lt;/strong&gt; Due to strong electrostatic forces between ions, ionic compounds require significant energy to break the bonds.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2684&quot; data-start=&quot;2415&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Electrical conductivity:&lt;/strong&gt; Ionic compounds conduct electricity in molten or aqueous states as ions are free to move.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2860&quot; data-start=&quot;2735&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Solubility:&lt;/strong&gt; Ionic compounds are generally soluble in polar solvents like water.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3071&quot; data-start=&quot;2865&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Crystalline structure:&lt;/strong&gt; Ionic compounds form well-defined crystals due to the orderly arrangement of ions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications of NaCl:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3250&quot; data-start=&quot;3076&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Common salt:&lt;/strong&gt; NaCl is widely used as table salt in culinary practices.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3402&quot; data-start=&quot;3301&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Industrial use:&lt;/strong&gt; It serves as a raw material in the production of chemicals like sodium hydroxide (NaOH) and chlorine gas (Cl₂).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3580&quot; data-start=&quot;3407&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;De-icing:&lt;/strong&gt; NaCl is used to melt ice on roads during winter.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Difference between Ionic and Covalent Bonds:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;4636&quot; data-start=&quot;4411&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ionic bonds:&lt;/strong&gt; Formed by the transfer of electrons, leading to the creation of charged ions.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;4761&quot; data-start=&quot;4641&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Covalent bonds:&lt;/strong&gt; Formed by sharing electrons between atoms.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Examples of Ionic Compounds:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;5043&quot; data-start=&quot;4817&quot;&gt;Common examples include &lt;strong&gt;NaCl (sodium chloride)&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;MgO (magnesium oxide)&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;CaF₂ (calcium fluoride)&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;RBC rupture and toxin release every few days&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The periodic fever in malaria is caused by the synchronous rupture of infected red blood cells (RBCs) and the release of toxins, primarily &lt;strong&gt;hemozoin pigment and other inflammatory mediators&lt;/strong&gt;, into the bloodstream.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Plasmodium parasites undergo a complex life cycle, including asexual reproduction within RBCs, leading to their destruction every 48-72 hours depending on the species.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The cyclical nature of fever corresponds to the completion of the parasite&amp;#39;s schizogony stage within RBCs, which is synchronized across a population of parasites.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Species-specific periodicity: Plasmodium vivax and Plasmodium ovale cause fever every 48 hours, while Plasmodium malariae causes it every 72 hours, and Plasmodium falciparum often exhibits irregular fever patterns.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The toxins and metabolites released during RBC rupture trigger immune responses, including the release of cytokines like &lt;strong&gt;tumor necrosis factor-alpha (TNF-&amp;alpha;)&lt;/strong&gt;, leading to fever and other systemic symptoms.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Plasmodium Life Cycle:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The life cycle involves two hosts: humans and female Anopheles mosquitoes.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In humans, Plasmodium first infects liver cells (exo-erythrocytic stage) and then moves to RBCs (erythrocytic stage).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hemozoin:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A toxic byproduct of hemoglobin metabolism by Plasmodium parasites.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Hemozoin accumulation is a key factor in triggering immune responses and systemic inflammation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Periodic Fever Mechanism:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Caused by synchronized schizont rupture and immune system activation.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Cytokines like TNF-&amp;alpha; and interleukin-1 (IL-1) are released, leading to fever.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Plasmodium Species:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Four major human-infecting species: P. vivax, P. ovale, P. malariae, and P. falciparum.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;P. falciparum is the most dangerous, often causing severe and complicated malaria.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Malaria Transmission:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Spread via bites of infected female Anopheles mosquitoes.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Control measures include insecticide-treated bed nets and antimalarial drugs.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;It allows the flow of heat between systems.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A diathermic wall is a type of boundary in thermodynamics that &lt;strong&gt;permits the transfer of heat&lt;/strong&gt; between two systems or between a system and its surroundings.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It does not allow the exchange of matter between systems, ensuring that the systems remain physically separate.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Diathermic walls are typically used in thermodynamic experiments to &lt;strong&gt;study heat transfer&lt;/strong&gt; while isolating other forms of energy transfer, such as work.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Heat transfer occurs because of the temperature difference between systems separated by a diathermic wall.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The concept of diathermic walls is crucial in understanding &lt;strong&gt;thermal equilibrium&lt;/strong&gt;, as heat flows until both systems reach the same temperature.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Main Theme: Thermodynamic Walls&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Thermodynamic walls are boundaries that separate systems and influence the type of interaction between them.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They can be classified into different types, including &lt;strong&gt;adiabatic walls&lt;/strong&gt; (prevent heat transfer), &lt;strong&gt;diathermic walls&lt;/strong&gt; (allow heat transfer), and &lt;strong&gt;rigid walls&lt;/strong&gt; (prevent work transfer).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The study of these walls helps in understanding the exchange of energy in various thermodynamic processes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Velocity&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Velocity&lt;/strong&gt; is a vector quantity, meaning it has both magnitude (speed) and direction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The formula for velocity is &lt;strong&gt;v = s/t&lt;/strong&gt;, where &amp;quot;v&amp;quot; is velocity, &amp;quot;s&amp;quot; is displacement, and &amp;quot;t&amp;quot; is time.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Unlike speed, which is scalar, velocity provides information about the direction of motion along with the rate of displacement.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;For instance, if an object moves 10 meters east in 2 seconds, its velocity would be 5 m/s east.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Velocity can be positive, negative, or zero, depending on the direction of motion relative to a chosen reference point.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Time&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Time is a scalar quantity, meaning it has magnitude but no direction.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a fundamental physical quantity that measures the progression of events from the past to the present and into the future.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The SI unit of time is the second (s).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In physics, time plays a crucial role in equations of motion, such as speed = distance/time.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Distance&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Distance is a scalar quantity that measures the total path covered by an object irrespective of direction.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is always positive and does not decrease, even if the object changes direction.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The SI unit of distance is the meter (m).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For example, if a person walks 5 meters forward and then 3 meters backward, the total distance covered is 8 meters.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Speed&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Speed is a scalar quantity that represents how fast an object is moving.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The formula for speed is &lt;strong&gt;speed = distance/time&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Unlike velocity, speed does not include direction; it only indicates the rate of motion.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The SI unit of speed is meters per second (m/s).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For example, a car traveling 60 km in 1 hour has a speed of 60 km/h.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Opposite to the direction of relative motion&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Frictional force always acts &lt;strong&gt;opposite to the direction of relative motion&lt;/strong&gt; or attempted motion between two surfaces in contact.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is a resistive force generated due to the interaction of surface irregularities at the molecular level.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The magnitude of the frictional force depends on the &lt;strong&gt;normal force&lt;/strong&gt; and the coefficient of friction between the surfaces.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Frictional force can be classified into &lt;strong&gt;static friction&lt;/strong&gt; (when there is no relative motion) and &lt;strong&gt;kinetic friction&lt;/strong&gt; (when motion occurs).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In real-life applications, friction plays a critical role in enabling activities such as walking, driving, and holding objects securely.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Frictional Force&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Friction is a fundamental force in physics that arises due to the interaction between two surfaces.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The coefficient of friction is a key parameter that quantifies the resistance offered by surfaces in contact.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Friction can be advantageous (e.g., providing grip) or disadvantageous (e.g., causing wear and energy loss).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Proteins,Carbohydrates and phospholipids.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;basic components of a cell are the cell membrane (plasma membrane), cytoplasm, and nucleus.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The cytoplasm and nucleus are enclosed within the&lt;strong&gt; cell membrane&lt;/strong&gt;, also called the &lt;strong&gt;plasma membrane.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The membrane separates cells from one another and also the cell from the surrounding medium.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Plasma membrane&lt;/strong&gt; forms the boundary of the cytoplasm, which is protected from the outside by the extracellular matrix.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is the&lt;strong&gt; innermost layer of the cell envelope.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;plasma membrane is primarily composed of a phospholipid bilayer with embedded proteins, glycolipids, and glycoproteins.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is &lt;strong&gt;semi-permeable in nature.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Plasma membrane is &lt;strong&gt;responsible for the interaction of the cell with the outside environment.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The plasma membrane is &lt;strong&gt;porous &lt;/strong&gt;and allows the movement of substances or materials both inward and outward.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/images/production/quesImages/qImage640c2d971414b1888a5af9ae.png&quot; style=&quot;height: 98px; width: 250px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Functions:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It helps in the regulation of the exchange of specific materials between the cytoplasm and extracellular medium.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Selectively permits particular molecules to pass and prevents others.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Prevents loss of components from the cells through leakage.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The plasma membrane is vital to cellular homeostasis and therefore, the health and welfare of all living organisms.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thus,&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;plasma membrane is composed of proteins,carbohydrates&amp;nbsp;and phospholipids.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
